Given our use cases, where we are working with a dataset of about 2GB and performing computationally intensive tasks like training XGBoost models and hyper-parameter tuning,  here’s a detailed comparison of Azure SSD options for our team, considering 2 scenarios: light concurrent usage and heavy computational tasks by a couple of users.
1. Standard SSD
•	Pros:
o	Cost-effective.
o	Suitable for general-purpose workloads.
•	Cons:
o	Lower IOPS (Input/Output Operations Per Second) and throughput compared to Premium SSDs.
•	Use Case:
o	Light Concurrent Usage: When multiple users are working simultaneously but not performing computationally heavy tasks, a Standard SSD may suffice. It can handle data manipulation and basic model training without significantly impacting performance.
o	Heavy Computational Usage: If a couple of users are running computationally intensive tasks like hyper-parameter tuning or large-scale model training, the Standard SSD might struggle to keep up, leading to slower performance and potential bottlenecks.
2. Premium SSD
•	Pros:
o	Higher IOPS and throughput.
o	Designed for high-performance applications and workloads requiring low latency.
•	Cons:
o	Higher cost compared to Standard SSD.
•	Use Case:
o	Light Concurrent Usage: Provides a performance buffer that ensures smooth operation even if a few users are working on moderately demanding tasks simultaneously. It offers better responsiveness than a Standard SSD in multi-user scenarios.
o	Heavy Computational Usage: Highly recommended if a couple of users are running computationally heavy tasks. The higher IOPS and throughput of a Premium SSD ensure that these tasks are completed efficiently, without causing significant delays or impacting other team members' work.
Summary:
•	For Light Concurrent Usage (Multiple Users, Not Computationally Heavy):
o	Standard SSD can be a cost-effective choice, but Premium SSD offers better performance, ensuring a smoother experience for all team members.
•	For Heavy Computational Usage (A Couple of Users Running Intensive Tasks):
o	Premium SSD is strongly recommended. It can handle the demands of intensive tasks like hyper-parameter tuning and large-scale model training without performance degradation, even in a multi-user environment.
In conclusion, Premium SSD is the better overall choice, providing the flexibility to handle both scenarios effectively. As our team's computational demands are mostly moderate and if we want to keep things cost effective, it could be a good idea to start with Standard SSD and upgrade if we observe performance issues during heavier workloads.



R vs Python for SSD
The performance considerations for disk storage (IOPS and throughput) are independent of the programming language we use, as they are more related to how data is read from and written to the disk and the computational demands of our tasks.
Why This Still Applies:
1.	Data Manipulation: Whether in R or Python, manipulating a dataset of 2 million rows and 100 columns (approximately 2GB) involves similar I/O operations, and the SSD’s performance will affect how quickly data can be read into memory and written back to disk.
2.	XGBoost and Computational Tasks: Training machine learning models and performing hyper-parameter tuning are computationally intensive tasks that rely heavily on both CPU/GPU resources and the underlying disk’s speed for reading data and writing temporary files. This is true regardless of whether we’re using R or Python.
3.	Multi-User Environment: When multiple users are working on a shared virtual server, the combined disk I/O from different users' R processes can add up, making a faster SSD (like Premium SSD) beneficial to avoid slowdowns.
Summary:
•	RStudio and R-based Workloads: The recommendations for Standard vs. Premium SSD apply equally to R, as they would to Python, because the underlying factors (data size, computational intensity, multi-user environment) are the same.
•	Premium SSD remains the recommended choice if we anticipate heavy computational tasks or multiple users working simultaneously. If our workloads are typically lighter, Standard SSD could suffice, but be prepared to upgrade if performance issues arise.

